Yes. That’s the pattern.

Subquadratic sparse attention means: don’t connect every token/person/company/event to every other one. Full attention is expensive: O(n^2). Sparse attention picks only the links that matter, often using local windows + global tokens + random/selected long-range links. BigBird, for example, reduced quadratic attention toward linear sparse attention while preserving key expressive properties with global tokens.  ￼

For Hold the Line, that means:

Don’t make every user evaluate every company.
Route attention through evidence nodes, trusted reviewers, local communities, campaign anchors, and global “signal tokens.”

The app architecture could be:

Local attention: users see companies relevant to their area, spending habits, industry, or current campaigns.

Global tokens: major campaigns, verified investigations, legal/regulatory actions, top extraction patterns.

Random/long-range links: occasional discovery of hidden connections: same PE owner, same supplier, same dark-pattern vendor, same shrinkflation pattern.

Sparse graph: user → issue → company → owner → evidence → alternative.

That keeps the system scalable and harder to drown in noise.

Pantheon translation:

Spider builds the sparse graph.
Hound detects anomaly/extraction patterns.
Mirror checks claims and evidence.
Checksum tracks provenance.
Goblin allocates attention budget.
Mother Duck keeps the ledger.

So “subquadratic sparse attention” becomes the governance principle:

Scale consumer coordination by routing attention through the few edges that carry the most truth, leverage, and action.